{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"295b4ae2-e144-4012-8486-8af924380f34","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes without `createdump`, you have two options:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** – macOS automatically generates `.ips` (or `.crash`) files in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain the stack trace, signal info, and thread state.\n\n2. **Core dumps** – Enable them with:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can inspect it with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./your-app\n   ```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report is usually the fastest path — check `DiagnosticReports` first since macOS generates it automatically with no prior setup needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"28798b9c-ca85-466c-9ba3-f604ba968e66","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to find crash dumps or crash reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` is not available. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":300,"requestId":"C3CE:61C51:1C437FD:1FD25AC:6A07C20F"},"id":"5bcc610a-16fc-4a23-b303-c8934b8f1013","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:02:17.694Z","parentId":"9c7f8f4c-7e2e-4855-acaa-011b198cde4e"}
